Types of EBS

gp2, gp3 (general purpose SSD) – used for general workloads, app servers, boot volumes
io1, io2 (provisioned IOPS SSD) – used for high-performance databases (like Oracle E-Business Suite DB)
st1 (throughput optimized HDD) – used for big data, logs, and data warehouses
sc1 (cold HDD) – used for archival and infrequently accessed data

👉 st1 and sc1 are HDD volumes, and:

❌ Not suitable for OS (root volume)
❌ Slower random I/O
✔️ Designed for data storage only

Key Limitation

👉 You CANNOT use st1 or sc1 as root (boot) volumes

That’s why they don’t appear in default launch options.

How to use st1 / sc1 then?

You can still use them like this:

Launch EC2 with gp3 (root volume)
Go to EBS Volumes
Create a new volume:
Select st1 or sc1
Attach it to the EC2 instance
Mount it inside OS

does ebs volume dynamically increase?

Yes, EBS volumes can be dynamically increased using Elastic Volumes without downtime, but we cannot decrease the size
After Increasing Size

Same as other volumes:
👉 You must extend filesystem inside OS


can we dynamically change the ebs type?


👉 You can change volume types like:

gp2 → gp3
gp3 → io1/io2
st1 → gp3

👉 And this can be done without stopping your Amazon EC2 instance.
